# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-ec2
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon announced a limited public beta test of EC2 on August 25, 2006, offering access on a first-come, first-served basis.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon added two new instance types (Large and Extra-Large) on October 16, 2007.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On May 29, 2008, two more types were added, High-CPU Medium and High-CPU Extra Large.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] There were twelve types of instances available.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon added three new features on March 27, 2008: static IP addresses, availability zones, and user-selectable kernels.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On August 20, 2008, Amazon added Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] This provides persistent storage, a feature that had been lacking since the service was introduced.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon EC2 went into full production when it dropped the beta label on October 23, 2008.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] These features were subsequently added on May 18, 2009.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon EC2 was developed mostly by a team in Cape Town, South Africa led by Chris Pinkham.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Pinkham provided the initial architecture guidance for EC2 and then built the team and led the development of the project along with Willem van Biljon.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Initially, EC2 used Xen virtualization exclusively.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] However, on November 6, 2017, Amazon announced the new C5 family of instances that were based on a custom architecture around the KVM hypervisor, called Nitro.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Each virtual machine, called an "instance", functions as a virtual private server.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon sizes instances based on "Elastic Compute Units".
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The performance of otherwise identical virtual machines may vary.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On November 28, 2017, AWS announced a bare-metal instance, a departure from exclusively offering virtualized instance types.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] As of April 2018, Amazon charged about $0.0058 per hour ($4.176 per month) for the smallest "Nano Instance" (t2.nano) virtual machine running Linux or Windows.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Storage-optimized instances cost as much as $4.992 per hour (i3.16xlarge).
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] "Reserved" instances can go as low as $2.50 per month for a three-year prepaid plan.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The data transfer charge ranges from free to $0.12 per gigabyte, depending on the direction and monthly volume (inbound data transfer is free on all AWS services).
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EC2 costs can be analyzed using the Amazon Cost and Usage Report.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] There are many different cost categories for EC2 including: hourly Instance Charges, Data Transfer, EBS Volumes, EBS Volume Snapshots, and Nat Gateway.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] As of December 2010 Amazon offered a bundle of free resource credits to new account holders.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The credits are designed to run a "micro" sized server, storage (EBS), and bandwidth for one year.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Unused credits cannot be carried over from one month to the next.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Reserved instances enable EC2 or RDS service users to reserve an instance for one or three years.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The corresponding hourly rate charged by Amazon to operate the instance is 35 to 75% lower than the rate charged for on-demand instances.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Reserved instances can be purchased with three different payment options: All Upfront, Partial Upfront and No Upfront.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The different purchase options allow for different structuring of payment models, with a larger discount given to customers that pay their reservation upfront.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Reserved Instances are purchased based on a resource commitment.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] These reservations are made based on an instance type and a count of that instance type.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] For example, you could reserve 100 i3.large instances for a 3-year term.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In September 2016, AWS announced several enhancements to Reserved instances, introducing a new feature called scope and a new reservation type called a Convertible.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In October 2017, AWS announced the allowance to subdivide the instances purchased for more flexibility.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Cloud providers maintain large amounts of excess capacity they have to sell or risk incurring losses.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon EC2 Spot instances are spare compute capacity in the AWS cloud available at up to 90% discount compared to On-Demand prices.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] As a trade-off, AWS offers no SLA on these instances and customers take the risk that it can be interrupted with only two minutes of notification when Amazon needs the capacity back.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Researchers from the Israeli Institute of Technology found that "they (Spot instances) are typically generated at random from within a tight price interval via a dynamic hidden reserve price".
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Some companies, like Spotinst, are using machine learning to predict spot interruptions up to 15 minutes in advance.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In November 2019, Amazon announced Savings Plans.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Savings Plans are an alternative to Reserved Instances that come in two different plan types: Compute Savings Plans and EC2 Instances Savings Plans.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Compute Savings Plans allow an organization to commit to EC2 and Fargate usage with the freedom to change region, family, size, availability zone, OS and tenancy inside the lifespan of the commitment.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EC2 Instance Savings plans provide a larger discount than Compute Savings Plans but are less flexible meaning a user must commit to individual instance families within a region to take advantage, but with the freedom to change instances within the family in that region.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] AWS uses the Cost Explorer to automatically calculate recommendations for the commitments you should make how that commitment will look like as a monthly charge on your AWS bill.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] AWS Savings Plans are purchased based on hourly spend commitment.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] This hourly commitment is made using the discounted pricing of the savings plan you are purchasing.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] For example, you could commit to spending $5 per hour, on a Compute Savings Plan, for a 3-year term.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] When it launched in August 2006, the EC2 service offered Linux and later Sun Microsystems' OpenSolaris and Solaris Express Community Edition.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In October 2008, EC2 added the Windows Server 2003 and Windows Server 2008 operating systems to the list of available operating systems.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In March 2011, NetBSD AMIs became available.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In November 2012, Windows Server 2012 support was added.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Since 2006, Colin Percival, a FreeBSD developer and Security Officer, solicited Amazon to add FreeBSD.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In November 2012, Amazon officially supported running FreeBSD in EC2.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The FreeBSD/EC2 platform is maintained by Percival who also developed the secure deduplicating Amazon S3-cloud based backup service Tarsnap.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon has their own Linux distribution based on Fedora and Red Hat Enterprise Linux as a low cost offering known as the Amazon Linux AMI.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Version 2013.03 included: Linux kernel, Java OpenJDK Runtime Environment and GNU Compiler Collection.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On November 30, 2020, Amazon announced that it would be adding macOS to the EC2 service.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Initial support was announced for macOS Mojave and macOS Catalina running on Mac Mini.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon Elastic Container Registry (ECR) is a Docker registry service for Amazon EC2 instances to access repositories and images.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (EKS) a managed Kubernetes service running on top of EC2 without needing to provision or manage instances.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] An EC2 instance may be launched with a choice of two types of storage for its boot disk or "root device." The first option is a local "instance-store" disk as a root device (originally the only choice).
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The second option is to use an EBS volume as a root device.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Instance-store volumes are temporary storage, which survive rebooting an EC2 instance, but when the instance is stopped or terminated (e.g., by an API call, or due to a failure), this store is lost.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) provides raw block devices that can be attached to Amazon EC2 instances.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] These block devices can then be used like any raw block device.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In a typical use case, this would include formatting the device with a filesystem and mounting it.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In addition, EBS supports a number of advanced storage features, including snapshotting and cloning.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EBS volumes are built on replicated storage, so that the failure of a single component will not cause data loss.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EBS was introduced to the general public by Amazon in August 2008.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EBS volumes provide persistent storage independent of the lifetime of the EC2 instance, and act much like hard drives on a real server.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] More accurately, they appear as block devices to the operating system that are backed by Amazon's disk arrays.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The OS is free to use the device however it wants.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In the most common case, a file system is loaded and the volume acts as a hard drive.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Another possible use is the creation of RAID arrays by combining two or more EBS volumes.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] RAID allows increases of speed and/or reliability of EBS.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Users can set up and manage storage volumes of sizes from 1 GB to 16 TB.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The volumes support snapshots, which can be taken from a GUI tool or the API.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EBS volumes can be attached or detached from instances while they are running, and moved from one instance to another.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Simple Storage Service (S3) is a storage system in which data is accessible to EC2 instances, or directly over the network to suitably authenticated callers (all communication is over HTTP).
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon does not charge for the bandwidth for communications between EC2 instances and S3 storage "in the same region." Accessing S3 data stored in a different region (for example, data stored in Europe from a US East Coast EC2 instance) will be billed at Amazon's normal rates.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] S3-based storage is priced per gigabyte per month.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] For example, Apache Hadoop supports a special s3: filesystem to support reading from and writing to S3 storage during a MapReduce job.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] There are also S3 filesystems for Linux, which mount a remote S3 filestore on an EC2 image, as if it were local storage.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] As S3 is not a full POSIX filesystem, things may not behave the same as on a local disk (e.g., no locking support).
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon's elastic IP address feature is similar to static IP address in traditional data centers, with one key difference.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] A user can programmatically map an elastic IP address to any virtual machine instance without a network administrator's help and without having to wait for DNS to propagate the binding.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In this sense an Elastic IP Address belongs to the account and not to a virtual machine instance.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] It exists until it is explicitly removed, and remains associated with the account even while it is associated with no instance.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon CloudWatch is a web service that provides real-time monitoring to Amazon's EC2 customers on their resource utilization such as CPU, disk, network and replica lag for RDS Database replicas.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] CloudWatch does not provide any memory, disk space, or load average metrics without running additional software on the instance.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Since December 2017 Amazon provides a CloudWatch Agent for Windows and Linux operating systems included disk and previously not available memory information, previously Amazon provided example scripts for Linux instances to collect OS information.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The data is aggregated and provided through AWS management console.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] It can also be accessed through command line tools and Web APIs, if the customer desires to monitor their EC2 resources through their enterprise monitoring software.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon provides an API which allows clients to operate on CloudWatch alarms.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The metrics collected by Amazon CloudWatch enables the auto-scaling feature to dynamically add or remove EC2 instances.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The customers are charged by the number of monitoring instances.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Since May 2011, Amazon CloudWatch accepts custom metrics that can be submitted programmatically via Web Services API and then monitored the same way as all other internal metrics, including setting up the alarms for them, and since July 2014 Cloudwatch Logs service is also available.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Basic Amazon CloudWatch is included in Amazon Free Tier service.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon's auto-scaling feature of EC2 allows it to automatically adapt computing capacity to site traffic.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The schedule-based (e.g. time-of-the-day) and rule-based (e.g.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] CPU utilization thresholds) auto scaling mechanisms are easy to use and efficient for simple applications.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] However, one potential problem is that VMs may take up to several minutes to be ready to use, which are not suitable for time critical applications.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The VM startup time is dependent on image size, VM type, data center locations, etc.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The convenience of using EC2 enables you to dynamically increase capacity in accordance with demand and access resources rapidly.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On Demand EC2 instances are priced per hour.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] An example of this pricing would be $0.096 per hour for a Linux, m5.large, EC2 instance in the us-east-1 region.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Pricing will vary based on the instance type, region, and operating system of the instance.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Public on-demand pricing for EC2 can be found on the AWS website.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The other pricing models for EC2 have different pricing models.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Spot instances also have a cost per instance hour, but the cost will change on a regular basis based on the supply of EC2 spot capacity.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Reserved Instances and Compute Savings plans are priced per hour.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Each of these reservation tools has its own price per hour based on the payment option, term and reservation product being used.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] These prices are locked in for either a 1-year or 3-year term.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon EC2 price varies from $2.5 per month for "nano" instance with 1 vCPU and 0.5 GB RAM on board to "xlarge" type of instances with 32 vCPU and 488 GB RAM billed up to $3997.19 per month.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The charts above show how Amazon EC2 pricing is compared to similar Cloud Computing services: Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, Kamatera, and Vultr.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] To make EC2 more fault-tolerant, Amazon engineered *Availability Zones* that are designed to be insulated from failures in other availability zones.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Availability zones do not share the same infrastructure.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Applications running in more than one availability zone can achieve higher availability.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EC2 provides users with control over the geographical location of instances that allows for latency optimization and high levels of redundancy.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] For example, to minimize downtime, a user can set up server instances in multiple zones that are insulated from each other for most causes of failure such that one backs up the other.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Higher-availability database services, like Amazon Relational Database Service run separately from EC2 instances.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In early July 2008, the anti-spam organizations Outblaze and Spamhaus.org began blocking Amazon's EC2 address pool due to problems with the distribution of spam and malware.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On December 1, 2010, Amazon pulled its service to WikiLeaks after coming under political pressure in the US.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Assange said that WikiLeaks chose Amazon knowing it would probably be kicked off the service "in order to separate rhetoric from reality".
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The Internet group Anonymous attempted to attack EC2 in revenge; however, Amazon was not affected by the attack.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon's websites were temporarily offline on December 12, 2010, although it was initially unclear if this was due to attacks or a hardware failure.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] An Amazon official later stated that it was due to a hardware failure.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Shortly before 5 am ET on April 21, 2011, an outage started at EC2's Northern Virginia data center that brought down several websites, including Foursquare, Springpad, Reddit, Quora, and Hootsuite.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Specifically, attempts to use Amazon's elastic-disk and database services hung, failed, or were slow.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Service was restored to some parts of the data center (three of four "availability zones" in Amazon's terms) by late afternoon Eastern time that day; problems for at least some customers were continuing as of April 25.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] 0.07% of EBS volumes in one zone have also been lost; EBS failures were a part of normal operation even before this outage and were a risk documented by Amazon, though the number of failures and the number of *simultaneous* failures may find some EC2 users unprepared.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On Sunday August 6, 2011, Amazon suffered a power outage in one of their Ireland availability zones.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Lightning was originally blamed for the outage; however, on August 11, Irish energy supplier ESB Networks dismissed this as a cause, but at time of writing, could not confirm what the cause of the problem was.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The power outage raised multiple questions regarding Amazon's EBS infrastructure, which caused several bugs in their software to be exposed.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The bugs resulted in some customers' data being deleted when recovering EBS volumes in a mid-write operation during the crash.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] August 8, 2011, saw another network connectivity outage of Amazon's Northern Virginia data center, knocking out the likes of Reddit, Quora, Netflix and FourSquare.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Another Northern Virginia data center outage occurred on October 22, 2012, from approximately 10 am to 4 pm PT.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Edmodo, Airbnb, Flipboard, Reddit, and other customers were affected.
[src:aws-ec2/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Anonymous claimed responsibility, but Amazon denied this assertion.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Cloud computing architectures consist of front-end platforms called clients or cloud clients.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] These clients are servers, fat (or thick) clients, thin clients, zero clients, tablets and mobile devices that users directly interact with.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] These client platforms interact with the cloud data storage via an application (middle ware), via a web browser, or through a virtual session.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Virtual sessions in particular require secure encryption algorithm frame working which spans the entire interface.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] The zero or ultra-thin client initializes the network to gather required configuration files that then tell it where its OS binaries are stored.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] The entire zero client device runs via the network.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] This creates a single point of failure, in that, if the network goes down, the device is rendered useless.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] An online network storage where data is stored and accessible to multiple clients.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Cloud storage is generally deployed in the following configurations: public cloud, private cloud, community cloud, or some combination of the three also known as hybrid cloud.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] In order to be effective, the cloud storage needs to be agile, flexible, scalable, multi-tenancy, and secure.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] The software-as-a-service (SaaS) service-model involves the cloud provider installing and maintaining software in the cloud and users running the software from the cloud over the Internet (or intranet).
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] The users' client machines require no installation of any application-specific software since cloud applications run in the cloud.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] SaaS is scalable, and system administrators may load the applications on several servers.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] In the past, each customer would purchase and load their own copy of the application to each of their own servers, but with SaaS, the customer can access the application without installing the software locally.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] SaaS typically involves a monthly or annual fee.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Software as a service provides the equivalent of installed applications in the traditional (non-cloud computing) delivery of applications.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Of these, flex tenancy is considered the most user adaptive SaaS paradigm in designated multi-input four way manifold models.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Such systems are based on simplified encryption methods that target listed data sequences over multiple passes.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] The simplicity of this concept makes flex tenancy SaaS popular among those without informatics processing experience, such as basic maintenance and custodial staff in franchise businesses.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Development as a service is a web-based, community shared toolset.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] This is the equivalent to locally installed development tools in the traditional (non-cloud computing) delivery of development tools.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Data as a service web based design construct where cloud data is accessed through a defined API layer.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] DaaS services are often considered as a specialized subset of a Software as a Service (SaaS) offering.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Platform as a service is cloud computing service which provides the users with application platforms and databases as a service.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] This is equivalent to middleware in the traditional (non-cloud computing) delivery of application platforms and databases.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Infrastructure as a service is taking the physical hardware and going completely virtual (e.g., all servers, networks, storage, and system management all exist in the cloud).
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] This is the equivalent to infrastructure and hardware in the traditional (non-cloud computing) method running in the cloud.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] In other words, businesses pay a fee (monthly or annually) to run virtual servers, networks,and storage from the cloud.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] This will mitigate the need for a data center, heating, cooling, and maintaining hardware at the local level .
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Allowing users to have uninterrupted access to their data and applications.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] On-demand access to resources requires the ability to move quickly and efficiently between servers and possibly even clouds.
[src:aws-ec2/cloud-computing-architecture] Security is always important, but when you are dealing with multi-tenancy, it becomes much more important because you're dealing with segregating multiple customers.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] In computing, **elasticity** is defined as "the degree to which a system is able to adapt to workload changes by provisioning and de-provisioning resources in an autonomic manner, such that at each point in time the available resources match the current demand as closely as possible".
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Elasticity is a defining characteristic that differentiates cloud computing from previously proposed distributed computing paradigms, such as grid computing.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] The dynamic adaptation of capacity, e.g., by altering the use of computing resources, to meet a varying workload is called "elastic computing".
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] In the world of distributed systems, there are several definitions according to the authors; some consider the concepts of scalability a sub-part of elasticity, others as being distinct.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Elasticity aims to match the amount of resources allocated to a service with the amount of resources it actually requires, avoiding over- or under-provisioning.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] **Over-provisioning**, i.e., allocating more resources than required, should be avoided as it may incur extra costs (monetary, energy, operational, etc.) for unused or underutilized resources.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] For example, if a website is over-provisioned with two cloud computing resources to handle current demand that only requires one resource, the costs of maintaining the second resource would effectively be wasted.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Elasticity can be illustrated through an example of a service provider who wants to run a website on the cloud.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] At moment $t_{0}$ , the website is unpopular and a single machine is sufficient to serve all users.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] At moment $t_{1}$ , the website suddenly becomes popular, and a single machine is no longer sufficient to serve all users.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Based on the number of web users simultaneously accessing the website and the resource requirements of the web server, ten machines are needed.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and provision nine additional machines from the cloud to serve all users responsively.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] At time $t_{2}$ , the website becomes unpopular again.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] The ten machines currently allocated to the website are mostly idle and a single machine would be sufficient to serve the few users who are accessing the website.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and deprovision nine machines, releasing them to the cloud.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] A cloud virtual machine (VM) can be acquired at any time by the user; however, it may take up to several minutes for the acquired VM to be ready to use.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] The VM startup time is dependent on factors such as image size, VM type, data center location, number of VMs, etc.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Cloud providers have different VM startup performance.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] This implies that any control mechanism designed for elastic applications must consider the time needed for the resource provisioning actions to take effect.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Elastic applications can allocate and deallocate resources on demand for specific application components.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] This makes cloud resources volatile, and traditional monitoring tools which associate monitoring data with a particular resource, such as Ganglia or Nagios, are no longer suitable for monitoring the *behavior* of elastic applications.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] For example, during its lifetime, a data storage tier of an elastic application might add and remove data storage VMs due to cost and performance requirements, varying the number of used VMs.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Thus, additional information is needed in monitoring elastic applications, such as associating the logical application structure over the underlying virtual infrastructure.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] When deploying applications in cloud infrastructures (IaaS/PaaS), stakeholder requirements need to be considered in order to ensure that elastic behavior meets stakeholder needs.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Traditionally, the optimal trade-off between cost and quality or performance is considered; however, for real world cloud users, requirements regarding elastic behavior are more complex and target multiple dimensions of elasticity (e.g., SYBL).
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Cloud applications vary in type and complexity, with multiple levels of artifacts deployed in layers.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Controlling such structures must take into consideration a variety of issues.
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] Elastic strategies on in cloud computing can take advantage of control-theoretic methods (e.g., predictive control has been experimented in cloud computing scenarios by showing considerable advantages with respect to reactive methods).
[src:aws-ec2/elastic-computing] One approach to multi-level elastic clouc control is rSYBL.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] A **hypervisor**, also known as a **virtual machine monitor** (**VMM**), is a type of computer software, firmware or hardware that creates and runs virtual machines.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] A computer on which a hypervisor runs one or more virtual machines is called a *host machine* or *virtualization server*, and each virtual machine is called a *guest machine*.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] The hypervisor presents the guest operating systems with a virtual operating platform and manages the execution of the guest operating systems.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Unlike an emulator, the guest executes most instructions on the native hardware.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Multiple instances of a variety of operating systems may share the virtualized hardware resources: for example, Linux, Windows, and macOS instances can all run on a single physical x86 machine.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] This contrasts with operating system-level virtualization, where all instances (usually called *containers*) must share a single kernel, though the guest operating systems can differ in user space, such as different Linux distributions with the same kernel.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] The term *hypervisor* is a variant of *supervisor*, a traditional term for the kernel of an operating system: the hypervisor is the supervisor of the supervisors, with *hyper-* used as a stronger variant of *super-*.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] The term dates to circa 1970; IBM coined it for software that ran OS/360 and the 7090 emulator concurrently on the 360/65 and later used it for the DIAG handler of CP-67.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] In the earlier CP/CMS (1967) system, the term *Control Program* was used instead.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Some literature, especially in microkernel contexts, makes a distinction between *hypervisor* and *virtual machine monitor* (*VMM*).
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] There, both components form the overall *virtualization stack* of a certain system.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] *Hypervisor* refers to kernel-space functionality and VMM to user-space functionality.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Specifically in these contexts, a *hypervisor* is a microkernel implementing virtualization infrastructure that must run in kernel-space for technical reasons, such as Intel VMX.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Microkernels implementing virtualization mechanisms are also referred to as *microhypervisor*.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Applying this terminology to Linux, KVM is a *hypervisor* and QEMU or Cloud Hypervisor are VMMs utilizing KVM as hypervisor.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] In his 1973 thesis *Architectural Principles for Virtual Computer Systems*, Robert P.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] These hypervisors run directly on the host's hardware to control the hardware and to manage guest operating systems.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] The first hypervisors, which IBM developed in the 1960s, were native hypervisors.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] These hypervisors run on a conventional operating system (OS) just as other computer programs do.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Type-2 hypervisors abstract guest operating systems from the host operating system, effectively creating an isolated system that can be interacted with by the host.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] The distinction between these two types is not always clear.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] For instance, KVM and bhyve are kernel modules that effectively convert the host operating system to a type-1 hypervisor.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] The first hypervisors providing full virtualization were the test tool SIMMON and the one-off IBM CP-40 research system, which began production use in January 1967 and became the first version of the IBM CP/CMS operating system.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] CP-40 ran on a S/360-40 modified at the Cambridge Scientific Center to support dynamic address translation, a feature that enabled virtualization.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Prior to this time, computer hardware had only been virtualized to the extent to allow multiple user applications to run concurrently, such as in CTSS and IBM M44/44X.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] With CP-40, the hardware's *supervisor state* was virtualized as well, allowing multiple operating systems to run concurrently in separate virtual machine contexts.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Programmers soon implemented CP-40 (as CP-67) for the IBM System/360-67, the first production computer system capable of full virtualization.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] IBM shipped this machine in 1966; it included page-translation-table hardware for virtual memory and other techniques that allowed a full virtualization of all kernel tasks, including I/O and interrupt handling.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] (The "official" operating system, the ill-fated TSS/360, did not employ full virtualization.) Both CP-40 and CP-67 began production use in 1967.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] CP/CMS was available to IBM customers from 1968 to early 1970s, in source code form without support.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] CP/CMS formed part of IBM's attempt to build robust time-sharing systems for its mainframe computers.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] By running multiple operating systems concurrently, the hypervisor increased system robustness and stability: Even if one operating system crashed, the others would continue working without interruption.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Indeed, this even allowed beta or experimental versions of operating systems‍—‌or even of new hardware‍—‌to be deployed and debugged, without jeopardizing the stable main production system, and without requiring costly additional development systems.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] IBM announced its System/370 series in 1970 without the virtual memory feature needed for virtualization, but added it in the August 1972 Advanced Function announcement.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Virtualization has been featured in all successor systems, such that all modern-day IBM mainframes, including the zSeries line, retain backward compatibility with the 1960s-era IBM S/360 line.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] The 1972 announcement also included VM/370, a reimplementation of CP/CMS for the S/370.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Unlike CP/CMS, IBM provided support for this version (though it was still distributed in source code form for several releases).
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] *VM* stands for *Virtual Machine*, emphasizing that all, not just some, of the hardware interfaces are virtualized.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Both VM and CP/CMS enjoyed early acceptance and rapid development by universities, corporate users, and time-sharing vendors, as well as within IBM.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Users played an active role in ongoing development, anticipating trends seen in modern open source projects.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] However, in a series of disputed and bitter battles, time-sharing lost out to batch processing through IBM political infighting, and VM remained IBM's "other" mainframe operating system for decades, losing to MVS.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] It enjoyed a resurgence of popularity and support from 2000 as the z/VM product, for example as the platform for Linux on IBM Z.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] As mentioned above, the VM control program includes a *hypervisor-call* handler that intercepts DIAG ("Diagnose", opcode x'83') instructions used within a virtual machine.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] This provides fast-path non-virtualized execution of file-system access and other operations (DIAG is a model-dependent privileged instruction, not used in normal programming, and thus is not virtualized.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] It is therefore available for use as a signal to the "host" operating system).
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] When first implemented in CP/CMS release 3.1, this use of DIAG provided an operating system interface that was analogous to the System/360 Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), but that did not require altering or extending the system's virtualization of SVC.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] In 1985 IBM introduced the PR/SM hypervisor to manage logical partitions (LPAR).
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Major Unix vendors, including HP, IBM, SGI, and Sun Microsystems, have been selling virtualized hardware since before 2000.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] These have generally been large, expensive systems (in the multimillion-dollar range at the high end), although virtualization has also been available on some low- and mid-range systems, such as IBM pSeries servers, HP Superdome series machines, and Sun/Oracle SPARC T series CoolThreads servers.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] IBM provides virtualization partition technology known as logical partitioning (LPAR) on System/390, zSeries, pSeries and IBM AS/400 systems.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] For IBM's Power Systems, the POWER Hypervisor (PHYP) is a native (bare-metal) hypervisor in firmware and provides isolation between LPARs.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Processor capacity is provided to LPARs in either a dedicated fashion or on an entitlement basis where unused capacity is harvested and can be re-allocated to busy workloads.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Groups of LPARs can have their processor capacity managed as if they were in a "pool" - IBM refers to this capability as Multiple Shared-Processor Pools (MSPPs) and implements it in servers with the POWER6 processor.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] LPAR and MSPP capacity allocations can be dynamically changed.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Memory is allocated to each LPAR (at LPAR initiation or dynamically) and is address-controlled by the POWER Hypervisor.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] For real-mode addressing by operating systems (AIX, Linux, IBM i), the Power processors (POWER4 onwards) have designed virtualization capabilities where a hardware address-offset is evaluated with the OS address-offset to arrive at the physical memory address.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Input/Output (I/O) adapters can be exclusively "owned" by LPARs or shared by LPARs through an appliance partition known as the Virtual I/O Server (VIOS).
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] HPE provides HP Integrity Virtual Machines (Integrity VM) to host multiple operating systems on their Itanium powered Integrity systems.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Itanium can run HP-UX, Linux, Windows and OpenVMS, and these environments are also supported as virtual servers on HP's Integrity VM platform.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] While it heavily leverages HP-UX, the Integrity VM hypervisor is really a hybrid that runs on bare-metal while guests are executing.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Running normal HP-UX applications on an Integrity VM host is heavily discouraged, because Integrity VM implements its own memory management, scheduling and I/O policies that are tuned for virtual machines and are not as effective for normal applications.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] HPE also provides more rigid partitioning of their Integrity and HP9000 systems by way of VPAR and nPar technology, the former offering shared resource partitioning and the latter offering complete I/O and processing isolation.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] The flexibility of virtual server environment (VSE) has given way to its use more frequently in newer deployments.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Wind River "Carrier Grade Linux" also runs on Sun's Hypervisor.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Full virtualization on SPARC processors proved straightforward: since its inception in the mid-1980s Sun deliberately kept the SPARC architecture clean of artifacts that would have impeded virtualization.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Similar trends have occurred with x86/x86-64 server platforms, where open-source projects such as Xen have led virtualization efforts.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] These include hypervisors built on Linux and Solaris kernels as well as custom kernels.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Since these technologies span from large systems down to desktops, they are described in the next section.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] x86 virtualization was introduced in the 1990s, with its emulation being included in Bochs.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Intel and AMD released their first x86 processors with hardware virtualisation in 2005 with Intel VT-x (code-named Vanderpool) and AMD-V (code-named Pacifica).
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] An alternative approach requires modifying the guest operating system to make a system call to the underlying hypervisor, rather than executing machine I/O instructions that the hypervisor simulates.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] This is called paravirtualization in Xen, a "hypercall" in Parallels Workstation, and a "DIAGNOSE code" in IBM VM.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Some microkernels, such as Mach and L4, are flexible enough to allow paravirtualization of guest operating systems.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Embedded hypervisors, targeting embedded systems and certain real-time operating system (RTOS) environments, are designed with different requirements when compared to desktop and enterprise systems, including robustness, security and real-time capabilities.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] The resource-constrained nature of multiple embedded systems, especially battery-powered mobile systems, imposes a further requirement for small memory-size and low overhead.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Finally, in contrast to the ubiquity of the x86 architecture in the PC world, the embedded world uses a wider variety of architectures and less standardized environments.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Support for virtualization requires memory protection (in the form of a memory management unit or at least a memory protection unit) and a distinction between user mode and privileged mode, which rules out most microcontrollers.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] This still leaves x86, MIPS, ARM and PowerPC as widely deployed architectures on medium- to high-end embedded systems.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] As manufacturers of embedded systems usually have the source code to their operating systems, they have less need for full virtualization in this space.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Instead, the performance advantages of paravirtualization make this usually the virtualization technology of choice.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Nevertheless, ARM and MIPS have recently added full virtualization support as an IP option and has included it in their latest high-end processors and architecture versions, such as ARM Cortex-A15 MPCore and ARMv8 EL2.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] Implementation of the concept has allegedly occurred in the SubVirt laboratory rootkit (developed jointly by Microsoft and University of Michigan researchers) as well as in the Blue Pill malware package.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] However, such assertions have been disputed by others who claim that it would be possible to detect the presence of a hypervisor-based rootkit.
[src:aws-ec2/hypervisor] In 2009, researchers from Microsoft and North Carolina State University demonstrated a hypervisor-layer anti-rootkit called Hooksafe that can provide generic protection against kernel-mode rootkits.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS-cloud providers supply resources on-demand from the large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks, VPNs).
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] To deploy their applications, users install operating-system images and the application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] Users patch and maintain the operating systems.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS services are typically billed as a utility: cost reflects the amount of resources allocated or consumed.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] Typically, IaaS involves the use of a cloud orchestration technology such as OpenStack, Apache CloudStack, or OpenNebula.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] It manages the creation of a virtual machine (VM) and decides on the hypervisor (i.e. physical host) in order to start it.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] A hypervisor runs virtual machines (VMs) as guests.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] Pools of hypervisors in the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to demand by customers.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] Hypervisors include Xen, Oracle VirtualBox, Oracle VM, KVM, VMware ESX/ESXi, or Microsoft Hyper-V.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] It also enables VM migration between hosts, allocates storage volumes, and attaches them to VMs that track usage information for billing.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] An alternative to hypervisors is Linux containers, which run in isolated partitions of a Linux kernel that runs directly on the physical hardware.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containers are isolated, secured and managed using Linux cgroups and namespaces.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containerisation offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] The global IaaS market is projected to reach a value of $411.9 billion by 2030, expanding at a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 22.6% from 2023 to 2030.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] This growth is primarily driven by the adoption of cloud-based infrastructure within the Banking, Financial Services, and Insurance (BFSI) sector, which employs these technologies to enhance scalability and reduce operational costs.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to use public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:aws-ec2/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS is in use within the UK Government but the technology community within government recommends consideration of Platform as a Service (PaaS) in cases where a department may not have IaaS skills and management capacity.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:aws-ec2/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
